h3. Summary

When a Jira instance scales on a high number of custom fields, the ability to manage these fields across the application becomes a challenge as we cannot perceive consistency in how the fields are displayed and also on the ability to search for them.

Some of the challenges are:

* There is no consistency in how the fields are displayed. On some screens, they are displayed alphabetically, while on others the order is different -- for example on Dashboard's gadgets;
* Most of the screens do not offer an option to search the fields, instead they display a drop-down with all the values (what can make it difficult to find the fields when considering more than 1,000 custom fields);
* Workflows conditions and validators are also hard to manage once you reach a certain number of custom fields since it also uses a drop-down list.

h3. Description

On the old issue editor/view, we had the ability to nest some tags like using nesting a code block within a panel, but on the new issue view they become two separate tags and we can't nest them.
h3. Suggestion

Add the ability to nest some tags on the new editor as used to do on the old one.
{noformat}
{panel}
 Panel content

  {code}
     code....
  {code}
{panel}

{noformat}

h3. Problem Definition

When creating a webhook, it is possible to use certain variables in the URL. These are currently restricted to:
{code:java}
{board.id}
{issue.id}
{issue.key}
{mergedVersion.id}
{modifiedUser.accountId}
{project.id}
{project.key}
{sprint.id}
{version.id}  
{code}
 
Source: [Webhooks|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/jira/platform/webhooks/]

However it would also be useful if there could be a variable that indicated the event type, such as issue created, issue edited, issue deleted, etc. In turn it would be helpful in some cases if this could be accessed with a variable name such as
{code:java}
${webhook.event} 
{code}
h3. Suggested Solution

Add
{code:java}
${webhook.event} 
{code}
as a valid variable.
h3. Why this is important

Improves the ability to integrate with other systems and more easily identify/share specific event types with those systems.

When opening an issue in Jira, clicking the three-dot menu and "print" will bring you to a view supposedly formatted for printing. Currently images in that view are not width restricted, making large images be clipped at the edge of the page. 

I've been adding the following CSS to allow the view to be successfully printed without clipping images…


{code:java}
img {
    max-width: 100%;
    width: auto;
    height: auto;
}
{code}
